{
  "texts": [
    "Textual data has attracted significant attention as a data source, for two different applications (Fig. 1).",
    "First, several tools have been developed for over a decade in educational technology (Aguiar et al., 2016; Burkhart et al., 2020; Qasim et al., 2013; Villalon and Calvo, 2011; Yang et al., 2022) so that educators could transform the written essays of their students into maps and then perform assessments through a dedicated network analysis software (Wang and Giabbanelli, 2023).",
    "Similar works have focused on extracting a map from an expert's text and using network analysis to dissect key concepts that should be passed onto students (Kim et al., 2020).",
    "Second, in a separate strand of literature, simulation and forecasting experts turn texts into maps for conceptual modeling and scenario-based foresight, respectively.",
    "Texts would be obtained (e.g., automatically via a web crawler) from sources that provide rich descriptions of the structure and dynamics of systems, such as expert interviews, white papers, or research articles (Bishop et al., 2007)."
  ]
}